Today, I received my rejection from MIT: 

<img src="data:image/png;base64,">

I'd been anxious to hear back from them for the past few weeks, and while I did think that it was a likely possibility that I would not make it through given that they hadn't interview me sooner, my natural optimism got the better of me. I can't say I'm not disappointed &mdash; or that I don't feel like the rejection affects my sense of self-worth to some degree; it does. However, I'm aware enough that this is not logical, nor is it productive. I'll take a minute, regroup and move on with my life. I didn't have a lot riding on this anyway, and frankly I wasn't really sure I'd take it if I got accepted anyway. I want to make a difference, and the degree &mdash; as nice as it would look on my wall &mdash; is not going to get me a whole lot closer to that goal anytime soon.

In the mean time, the plan hasn't changed: I want to continue to work on making Teleport a reality. To make a real difference to the lives of real people.

There are plenty of distractions &mdash; nice, shiny things that I think could make a meaningful difference to my well-being short term, but that contribute precious little to my long term plans. I feel like I need to continuously remind myself that my goal from life is not to live &mdash; but to serve some higher purpose. To help the Ummah reach new heights, as detailed in [my masterplan](/masterplan), whenever I get around to finishing that (whether it remains private, or is published).

I think what's going to be crucially important to me is to make sure that I give this effort my best shot &mdash; the last thing I want to live with is the burden of having known that I was given a chance to make a real difference, and the means to do so, and yet I squandered it. That is something I won't be able to live with. This stems from 1) an appreciation of the circumstances I find myself in (alhamdulillah) to be able to work on a project that promises no real, short-term income and yet still be able to do it &hellip; and 2) having the right intention throughout &mdash; namely, that I am doing this solely for the sake of Allah.

Alhamdullillah.
